:"djUE8ftygR"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":2,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The goal of this notebook is to learn how to load a collection of NetCDF files, chunk the data, write the data in Zarr format, and confirm the proper creation of the Zarr store.\nWe will be writing to our local storage for simplicity (as this is just a tutorial notebook), but you can easily change the output path to be anywhere including cloud storage.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"QvceA4SNlS"}],"key":"rA7cxlojPL"}],"key":"jUe4Ztl2ed"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"import fsspec\nimport xarray as xr\nimport numpy as np\nimport hvplot.xarray","key":"b11FPGXCVG"},{"type":"outputs","id":"E-VgvTEOETjIQOfklqKCB","children":[],"key":"RBj6jByzky"}],"key":"SOdqzHrOGQ"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example Dataset","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"PZ8AJ8tiwP"}],"identifier":"example-dataset","label":"Example Dataset","html_id":"example-dataset","implicit":true,"key":"ao730ZAQZS"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In this notebook, we will use the daily gridMET precipitation dataset as an example for reading data and writing to Zarr.\nThe data is currently hosted on the HyTEST OSN as a collection of NetCDF files.\nTo get the files, we will use ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"UnIc6avgpw"},{"type":"link","url":"https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"fsspec","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"ryTJMfQ9tM"}],"urlSource":"https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/","key":"jAPPV0I03v"},{"type":"text","value":" to open each year of precipitation data to a list.\nThen, we can read in the all the files at once using ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"FMySTVUuq0"},{"type":"link","url":"https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.open_mfdataset.html","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineCode","value":"xarray.open_mfdataset","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"nxqyHBc0YT"}],"urlSource":"https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.open_mfdataset.html","key":"OnnjPX7RrA"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"jiUp1xJu6E"}],"key":"JEgw75BH8Z"}],"key":"xlq7fv7H4y"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"fs = fsspec.filesystem(\n    's3',\n    anon=True,   # anonymous = does not require credentials\n    client_kwargs={'endpoint_url': 'https://usgs.osn.mghpcc.org/'}\n)\nprecip_files = [fs.open(file) for file in fs.glob('s3://mdmf/gdp/netcdf/gridmet/gridmet/pr_*.nc')]\nds = xr.open_mfdataset(\n    precip_files,\n    chunks={},\n    engine='h5netcdf'\n)\nds","key":"mpepltvMCV"},{"type":"outputs","id":"u3MNWIDSzEivYUQeqiE0y","children":[],"key":"wcpDdZnJhB"}],"key":"wLrpT5GQkt"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Selecting Chunk Shape and Size","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"L1YNaVXFfa"}],"identifier":"selecting-chunk-shape-and-size","label":"Selecting Chunk Shape and Size","html_id":"selecting-chunk-shape-and-size","implicit":true,"key":"oySHbLCJ2J"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As we can see in the rich HTML output of our dataset, the NetCDF files were already chunked with pattern of ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"LA9wRR1ZmE"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"{'day': 61, 'lat': 98, 'lon': 231}","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"ElkpXNZSYk"},{"type":"text","value":".\nHowever, the size of these chunks are relatively small and near the lower limit of an acceptable chunk size of 10 MiB.\nSo, it would be better if we could increase our chunk sizes to say 70-110 MiB.\nTo do this, we will simply use multiples of the current chunks so we don’t have to completely rechunk the dataset (grouping chunks is way faster than completely changing chunk shape).\nOur goal will be to try and evenly distribute the number of chunks between the time and space dimensions.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"s0B6WFoNvu"}],"key":"niUZ6ko1q7"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"First, let’s check how many chunks are in the temporal and spatial dimensions with the current chunk shape.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"zEDZZdMF7k"}],"key":"iMKJ8jCEbf"}],"key":"zAHwz057Vh"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"ds.precipitation_amount.encoding","key":"ZzNh7Pginv"},{"type":"outputs","id":"zok88IEmY3PCIEY-MjDsO","children":[],"key":"VQIkaMcUF9"}],"key":"AG31BwYNDq"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"time_chunk_shape, lat_chunk_shape, lon_chunk_shape = ds.precipitation_amount.encoding['chunksizes']\n\nprint(f\"Number of temporal chunks: {np.ceil(len(ds.day) / time_chunk_shape)}\")\nprint(f\"Number of spatial chunks: {np.ceil(len(ds.lat) / lat_chunk_shape) * np.ceil(len(ds.lon) / lon_chunk_shape)}\")","key":"DqO0dQqijK"},{"type":"outputs","id":"6oNNmBcrsLOPv5WGgcNti","children":[],"key":"H3QaM2aAEg"}],"key":"SOqMhZbPmy"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Okay, so there are about 7 times as many time chunks as there are spatial chunks.\nLet’s try to balance this better so there are an approximately equal amount.\nWe will do this by simply increasing the time chunk shape by a factor of 7.\nThen, we can double check our chunk size to see if it aligns with our chunk size goal.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"rcYaF8fPVW"}],"key":"e912wlnyQ4"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"qxCZJYCeAD"}],"key":"cWXR733Ury"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Also by increasing our temporal chunk shape by a factor of seven, it is now larger than a whole year.\nThis means if we only wanted a single year, we would at most need to read two chunks.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"NuGetbIZMT"}],"key":"xGTbM5akbI"}],"key":"bBc1CU1r0T"}],"key":"D4uSQdEBuC"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"chunk_plan = {\n    \"day\": time_chunk_shape * 7, \n    \"lat\" : lat_chunk_shape,\n    \"lon\" : lon_chunk_shape\n}\n\nbytes_per_value = ds.precipitation_amount.dtype.itemsize\n\nprint(f\"Chunk Plan:{chunk_plan}\")\nprint(f\"Number of temporal chunks: {np.ceil(len(ds.day) / chunk_plan['day'])}\")\nprint(f\"Number of spatial chunks: {np.ceil(len(ds.lat) / chunk_plan['lat']) * np.ceil(len(ds.lon) / chunk_plan['lon'])}\")\nprint(f\"Chunk size in MiB: {(bytes_per_value * chunk_plan['day'] * chunk_plan['lat'] * chunk_plan['lon']) / 2 ** 10 / 2 ** 10:0.2f}\")","key":"vfViFFesIR"},{"type":"outputs","id":"y7QHTHG7NkvFR_EUYM4xh","children":[],"key":"QbFQcpn1mW"}],"key":"rZv1bNKdeD"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Nice!\nThat got us the exact same number of chunks and the chunk size we were looking for.\nAs a final check, let’s make sure none of the ending chunks contain <50% data.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"S0iYD6IYyg"}],"key":"xdX2JZJKrY"}],"key":"RQ6iZp9iVK"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"print(f\"Number of day chunks: {(len(ds.day) / chunk_plan['day'])}\")\nprint(f\"Number of lat chunks: {(len(ds.lat) / chunk_plan['lat'])}\")\nprint(f\"Number of lon chunks: {(len(ds.lon) / chunk_plan['lon'])}\")","key":"sDOadirRZ6"},{"type":"outputs","id":"apL17s7k8kg2vq9SFZhWf","children":[],"key":"P2yJ9oYJgl"}],"key":"YtCG2NDXjg"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Perfect!\nSo the final day chunk is only 77% full, but that is good enough.\nLet’s now chunk the dataset to our chunking plan.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"EuCMc23RDu"}],"key":"XK4m94nmRq"}],"key":"CDkk7TwGLj"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-code","children":[{"type":"code","lang":"python","executable":true,"value":"ds = ds.chunk(chunk_plan)\nds","key":"X7LGSbEzzb"},{"type":"outputs","id":"IsT-WZjU